folder: Water Street & Catherine Slip, Manhattan, NY
text:
Water Street, at and adjoining the N.E. corner of Catherine Slip. Also shown is Catherine Slip, east side, north from Water, to and including Cherry Streets. Nos. 9-11 Catherine Slip, at and adjoining the N.E. corner of Water Street, are frame houses. No. 394 Water Street, adjoining the N.W. corner of Catherine Slip, is also a frame building.

About 1920.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.
title: Manhattan: Water Street - Catherine Slip

folder: Catherine Slip & Water Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
11 Catherine Slip, at and adjoining the N.E. corner of Water Street. Also shown is Water Street, at the N.E. corner of Catherine Slip. This is a 3-story frame house.

March 5, 1923.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.
title: Manhattan: Catherine Slip - Water Street

folder: Water Street & Catherine Slip, Manhattan, NY
text:
Water Street,North Side,looking Eastwards and across Catherine Slip,
October 8th,I938
P.L.Sperr,
No Reproductions.
(2)Same. Water Street,North Side,East from 386-392,a 1 story garage between Oliver St. and Catherine Slip. The three and four story structures adjoining same are numbers 394 Water Street and 10 Catherine Slip respectively. Across the Slip appear two frame structures;a one story affair at #11-9,both on Catherine Slip,at and adjoining the North East corner of Water Street. Partially shown on the right is the span of the Manhattan Bridge.
January 1924
Eugene L.Armbruster Collection,
May be reproduced.

folder: Water Street & Catherine Slip, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1)
Water Street, north side, east from Catherine Slip. Also shown is Catherine Slip, at and adjoining the N.E. corner of Water Street. 9 Catherine Slip, adjoining the N.E. corner of Water Street, is a frame house. (Direction of Water Street is arbitrarily set to run east and west).
September 7, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The same, showing a closer view of No. 396 Water Street, adjoining the N.E. corner of Catherine Slip, the home of "the second oldest Indian" in the United States.
September 7, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.

(3)
The same, showing a closer view of said antique.
September 7, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.
